{{Infobox person |name = Caroline Van Deusen Chenoweth |image = CAROLINE VAN DENSEN CHENOWETH.jpg |birth_date = {{date of birth|1846|12|29}} |death_date = 1917 |occupation = educator, diplomat}}
'''Caroline Van Deusen Chenoweth''' (December 29, 1846 &ndash; 1917) was an American educator and vice-consul for [[Guangdong|Canton]], China.<ref name=willard/><ref name=oaks/>
The daughter of Charles Van Deusen and Stary Huntington, she was born '''Caroline Van Deusen''' at the family's summer home on the [[Ohio River]] opposite [[Louisville, Kentucky]]. She was educated at the St. Charles Institute in [[New Orleans]] and at [[University of Evansville|Moores Hill College]]. She taught private classes in [[Boston]] and was a professor of English literature at [[Smith College]].<ref name=willard/>
She married Colonel Bernard Peel Chenoweth in 1863. Her husband served as American consul for Canton, China; during her husband's illness and for several months following his death in 1870, she served as vice-consul. Her name was put forward for the post of American consul; her candidacy was supported by President [[Ulysses S. Grant|Grant]] but was opposed by Secretary of State [[Hamilton Fish]].<ref name=willard/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=dpBJAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PR29 |title=The Arena |pages=xxix-xxx |volume=Volume 3 |year=1891}}</ref> In 1873, she was named a clerk at the Boston custom house.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=IGKlCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT13 |title=The Lives of Otto Chenoweth: Wyoming’s Gentleman Horse Thief |page=13 |last=Woods |first=Lawrence |year=2016 |ISBN=1504974158}}</ref>
Chenoweth founded the Colonel Timothy Bigelow Chapter of the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]].<ref name=oaks>{{cite web |url=https://revolutionaryoaks.wordpress.com/2014/12/20/the-oaks-of-christmas-present/ |title=The Oaks of Christmas Present |work=Revolutionary Oaks}}</ref> She was a member of the [[Society for Psychical Research]] in [[London]].<ref name=willard/>
She was author of ''Stories of the Saints''<ref name=willard>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=zXEEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA172 |title=A Woman of the Century: Fourteen Hundred-seventy Biographical Sketches Accompanied by Portraits of Leading American Women in All Walks of Life |pages=172-73 |last=Willard |first=Frances Elizabeth |author2=Livermore, Mary Ashton Rice |year=1893}}</ref> (1880), ''Child Life in China'' (1882) and ''Colonel John Hazeltine, an Undistinguished Citizen'' (1900).<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ebooksread.com/authors-eng/inc-marquis-whos-who/whos-who-in-america-volume-2-qra/page-51-whos-who-in-america-volume-2-qra.shtml |title=Who's who in America |volume=Volume 2 |year=1902 |page=200}}</ref>
