[[Image:NocturnalDisplay.jpg|thumb|200px|Animal in the nocturnal house at the [[Calgary Zoo]].]] A '''nocturnal house''', sometimes called a '''nocturama''',<ref>The Rotarian - Jan 1977 - Page 19 "Although ours is a private zoological organization, we still manage to operate an aquarium, a dolphinarium, a planetarium, a nocturama, a botanical garden, a museum of natural history, a public library, a natural reserve of some 100 hectares ..."</ref> is a [[building]] in a [[zoo]] or research establishment where [[nocturnal animal]]s are kept and viewable by the public. The unique feature of buildings of this type is that the [[lighting]] within is isolated from the outside and reversed; i.e. it is dark during the [[day]] and lit at [[night]]. This is to enable visitors and researchers to more conveniently study nocturnal animals during daylight hours.
Internally, a building usually consists of several glass-walled enclosures containing a replica of the animals' normal environments. In the case of burrowing animals, often their tunnels are 'half-glassed' so the animals can be observed while underground. ==References== {{reflist}}
